1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,520
API keys, database passwords, TLS certs.

2
00:00:06,520 --> 00:00:09,640
Don't put them in your image, use a secret.

3
00:00:09,640 --> 00:00:14,360
A secret is like a config map, but for sensitive data.

4
00:00:14,360 --> 00:00:17,640
Created independently of paths.

5
00:00:17,640 --> 00:00:20,640
Injected at runtime, not baked into the image.

6
00:00:20,640 --> 00:00:23,000
Here's the catch.

7
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:25,960
Secrets are not encrypted by default.

8
00:00:25,960 --> 00:00:28,200
They're base 64 encoded.

9
00:00:28,200 --> 00:00:30,600
That's encoding, not encryption.

10
00:00:30,600 --> 00:00:33,720
Anyone with ECT access can read them.

11
00:00:33,720 --> 00:00:38,040
To make secrets actually secret, enable encryption at rest

12
00:00:38,040 --> 00:00:39,960
and lock down RBAC.

13
00:00:39,960 --> 00:00:42,440
Three ways to use a secret.

14
00:00:42,440 --> 00:00:45,840
One, inject as environment variables.

15
00:00:45,840 --> 00:00:48,560
Two, mount as files in a volume.

16
00:00:48,560 --> 00:00:52,840
Three, image pull secret for private container registries.

17
00:00:52,840 --> 00:00:56,920
Use secrets, encrypt ed, restrict RBAC.

18
00:00:56,920 --> 00:00:59,440
Or use an external vault.

19
00:00:59,440 --> 00:01:02,560
Don't commit credentials to your image.

20
00:01:02,560 --> 00:01:06,360
Run the docs, Kubernetes secrets.

